Wireless Quantum Cryptographic Communication on Mars: A Theoretical Framework with Adaptive Stability

Author: Ouadi Maakoul
Date: March 2026
Status: PhD Draft v2.0 (Incorporating Stability Lemma and Adaptive Modes)

---

Abstract

We present a comprehensive theoretical framework for wireless quantum key distribution (QKD) on Mars, integrating experimentally validated atmospheric models with a novel adaptive error correction scheme that guarantees security even under extreme environmental fluctuations. The system exploits Mars’s thin atmosphere to reduce Rayleigh scattering while accounting for dust‑induced Mie extinction, charged‑dust enhancements (up to 200 % at high altitudes), and non‑stationary noise from dust storms and solar flares. We derive a Stability Lemma showing that encoding logical qubits into a decoherence‑free subspace (DFS) of two physical qubits filters out collective rotations, making the residual quantum bit error rate (QBER) scale quadratically with the rate of change of the dust load rather than its absolute magnitude. This enables operation during global dust storms where classical visibility drops to a few kilometers. From the lemma we extract operational constraints—correlation time requirements, mean photon number throttling, and residual error thresholds—and define four autonomous modes (clear sky, moderate dust, dust storm, solar flare) with corresponding repetition rates, encoding schemes, and predicted secure key rates. Using Mars Climate Database dust optical depth data, we estimate secure key rates up to 14 Mbit/s under clear conditions and 3 Mbit/s during dust storms, sufficient for future Martian habitats. A physical unclonable function (PUF)‑based bootstrap solves the classical channel authentication problem without pre‑shared secrets. This work establishes the mathematical and physical foundation for unconditionally secure, self‑healing communication infrastructure beyond Earth, directly applicable to autonomous extraterrestrial networks.

