Appendix B: Derivation of the Martian Channel Model

B.1 Mie Extinction Coefficient

The extinction coefficient due to dust is

\alpha_{\text{Mie}}(\lambda) = \int_0^\infty \pi r^2 Q_{\text{ext}}(r,\lambda,m) \, n(r) \, dr,

where Q_{\text{ext}} is the extinction efficiency factor computed from Mie theory, n(r) is the particle size distribution, and m is the complex refractive index of Martian dust. For a log‑normal distribution:

n(r) = \frac{N_0}{r \sigma \sqrt{2\pi}} \exp\left( -\frac{(\ln r - \ln r_m)^2}{2\sigma^2} \right),

with r_m = 1.5\ \mum, \sigma = 0.5, and N_0 proportional to the dust optical depth at a reference wavelength.

B.2 Charged‑Dust Correction

At altitudes z above 30 km, the extinction is multiplied by a factor \kappa_{\text{charge}}(z):

\alpha_{\text{charged}}(\lambda, z) = \kappa_{\text{charge}}(z) \, \alpha_{\text{Mie}}(\lambda),

where \kappa_{\text{charge}}(z) \in [1.6, 3.0] based on measurements by Gao et al. (2022). For surface‑to‑surface links, z \approx 0, so \kappa_{\text{charge}} = 1.

B.3 Composite CPTP Map

The overall channel is expressed in Kraus form:

\mathcal{E}_{\text{Mars}}(\rho) = \eta_{\text{total}} \left( (1-p_{\text{res}}) \rho + p_{\text{res}} \frac{I}{2} \right) + (1-\eta_{\text{total}}) \frac{I}{2},

with \eta_{\text{total}} = e^{-\alpha L} \eta_{\text{optics}} \eta_{\text{det}}. The first term represents a successful transmission followed by residual depolarization; the second term corresponds to a lost photon replaced by a maximally mixed state.

B.4 QBER Expression

For a depolarizing channel with efficiency \eta_{\text{total}} and residual error p_{\text{res}}, the QBER is

Q = \frac{1 - \eta_{\text{total}}}{2} + \frac{\eta_{\text{total}} p_{\text{res}}}{2}.

